{"parentUuid":"78640e9e-8509-42b4-890c-298d96435aa8","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"46e77d7e-3408-48fd-b50f-4c3f4002f80d","agentId":"ac7dc0987c25c56ae","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01N4ofsaK1JBfSnttBQ2ot1f","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/-\n     2→Copyright 2026 The Formal Conjectures Authors.\n     3→\n     4→Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n     5→you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n     6→You may obtain a copy of the License at\n     7→\n     8→    https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n     9→\n    10→Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n    11→distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n    12→WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n    13→See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n    14→limitations under the License.\n    15→-/\n    16→\n    17→import FormalConjectures.Util.ProblemImports\n    18→\n    19→/-!\n    20→# Erdős Problem 497\n    21→\n    22→How many antichains are there in the power set of an n-element set?\n    23→\n    24→*Reference:* [erdosproblems.com/497](https://www.erdosproblems.com/497)\n    25→\n    26→OEIS: [A000372](https://oeis.org/A000372)\n    27→\n    28→[Er61] Erdős, P., _Some unsolved problems_. Magyar Tud. Akad. Mat. Kutató Int. Közl. 6 (1961),\n    29→221–254.\n    30→\n    31→[Kl69] Kleitman, D., _On Dedekind's Problem: The Number of Monotone Boolean Functions_.\n    32→Proc. Amer. Math. Soc. 21 (1969), 677–682.\n    33→-/\n    34→\n    35→open Finset Filter\n    36→\n    37→namespace Erdos497\n    38→\n    39→open Classical in\n    40→/--\n    41→The number of antichains in the power set of $\\operatorname{Fin} n$ (the Dedekind number $D(n)$).\n    42→An antichain is a family $F$ of subsets of $[n]$ such that for all $A, B \\in F$,\n    43→$A \\neq B$ implies $A \\not\\subset B$.\n    44→-/\n    45→noncomputable def dedekindNumber (n : ℕ) : ℕ :=\n    46→  Fintype.card {F : Finset (Finset (Fin n)) // IsAntichain (· ⊆ ·) (F : Set (Finset (Fin n)))}\n    47→\n    48→/--\n    49→Erdős Problem 497 (Dedekind's Problem, resolved by Kleitman [Kl69]):\n    50→How many antichains in $[n]$ are there? That is, how many families of subsets\n    51→of $[n]$ are there such that no member is a subset of another?\n    52→\n    53→Sperner's theorem states that any single antichain has size at most\n    54→$\\binom{n}{\\lfloor n/2 \\rfloor}$. Kleitman proved that the total number of antichains in the\n    55→power set of $[n]$ is $2^{(1+o(1)) \\binom{n}{\\lfloor n/2 \\rfloor}}$.\n    56→\n    57→Equivalently, $\\log_2(D(n)) / \\binom{n}{\\lfloor n/2 \\rfloor} \\to 1$ as $n \\to \\infty$.\n    58→-/\n    59→@[category research solved, AMS 5 6]\n    60→theorem erdos_497 :\n    61→    Tendsto\n    62→      (fun n : ℕ => Real.log (dedekindNumber n : ℝ) / (Real.log 2 * (n.choose (n / 2) : ℝ)))\n    63→      atTop (nhds 1) := by\n    64→  sorry\n    65→\n    66→end Erdos497\n    67→"}]},"uuid":"d4c5b2f7-5313-44bf-9311-4a39dad7c1b3","timestamp":"2026-03-15T05:22:43.262Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"78640e9e-8509-42b4-890c-298d96435aa8","userType":"external","cwd":"/home/ryan/formal-conjectures","sessionId":"32eca89c-3188-4038-a46f-2447c61bd105","version":"2.1.74","gitBranch":"erdos-all","slug":"stateful-rolling-piglet"}
