{"parentUuid":"66724aeb-ce80-4192-8605-fa02dfc3a800","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"46e77d7e-3408-48fd-b50f-4c3f4002f80d","agentId":"ac7dc0987c25c56ae","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011tp8X42rGk9RYijmCskakX","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/-\n     2→Copyright 2026 The Formal Conjectures Authors.\n     3→\n     4→Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n     5→you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n     6→You may obtain a copy of the License at\n     7→\n     8→    https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n     9→\n    10→Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n    11→distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n    12→WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n    13→See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n    14→limitations under the License.\n    15→-/\n    16→\n    17→import FormalConjectures.Util.ProblemImports\n    18→\n    19→/-!\n    20→# Erdős Problem 164\n    21→\n    22→*Reference:* [erdosproblems.com/164](https://www.erdosproblems.com/164)\n    23→\n    24→[Er35] Erdős, P., *Note on sequences of integers no one of which is divisible by any other*.\n    25→J. London Math. Soc. (1935), 126-128.\n    26→\n    27→[Er76g] Erdős, P., *Problems and results on combinatorial number theory* (1976).\n    28→\n    29→[Er86] Erdős, P., *Some problems and results on combinatorial number theory* (1986).\n    30→\n    31→[Li23] Lichtman, J.D., *A proof of the Erdős primitive set conjecture*.\n    32→arXiv:2202.02384 (2023).\n    33→\n    34→[Va99] §1.12.\n    35→-/\n    36→\n    37→open Real\n    38→\n    39→namespace Erdos164\n    40→\n    41→/--\n    42→The Erdős primitive set conjecture (Problem 164) [Er76g, Er86]:\n    43→\n    44→For any primitive set $A \\subseteq \\{2, 3, 4, \\ldots\\}$ of natural numbers (i.e., an antichain\n    45→under divisibility), we have\n    46→$$\\sum_{n \\in A} \\frac{1}{n \\cdot \\log n} \\leq \\sum_{p \\text{ prime}} \\frac{1}{p \\cdot \\log p}.$$\n    47→\n    48→That is, the sum $\\sum \\frac{1}{n \\log n}$ over any primitive set is maximised when\n    49→the set is the set of all primes.\n    50→\n    51→Proved by Lichtman [Li23].\n    52→-/\n    53→@[category research solved, AMS 11]\n    54→theorem erdos_164 :\n    55→    ∀ A : Set ℕ, IsAntichain (· ∣ ·) A → A ⊆ {n : ℕ | 2 ≤ n} →\n    56→    ∑' n : A, (1 : ℝ) / (((n : ℕ) : ℝ) * Real.log ((n : ℕ) : ℝ)) ≤\n    57→    ∑' p : {p : ℕ | Nat.Prime p}, (1 : ℝ) / (((p : ℕ) : ℝ) * Real.log ((p : ℕ) : ℝ)) := by\n    58→  sorry\n    59→\n    60→/--\n    61→Erdős [Er35] proved that for any primitive set $A \\subseteq \\{2, 3, 4, \\ldots\\}$,\n    62→the sum $\\sum_{n \\in A} \\frac{1}{n \\log n}$ converges. This is a prerequisite for the\n    63→main conjecture `erdos_164`.\n    64→-/\n    65→@[category research solved, AMS 11]\n    66→theorem erdos_164_convergence :\n    67→    ∀ A : Set ℕ, IsAntichain (· ∣ ·) A → A ⊆ {n : ℕ | 2 ≤ n} →\n    68→    Summable (fun n : A => (1 : ℝ) / (((n : ℕ) : ℝ) * Real.log ((n : ℕ) : ℝ))) := by\n    69→  sorry\n    70→\n    71→end Erdos164\n    72→"}]},"uuid":"3f8abf21-a5d9-46ef-9ad1-fd827ec954d3","timestamp":"2026-03-15T05:22:54.839Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"66724aeb-ce80-4192-8605-fa02dfc3a800","userType":"external","cwd":"/home/ryan/formal-conjectures","sessionId":"32eca89c-3188-4038-a46f-2447c61bd105","version":"2.1.74","gitBranch":"erdos-all","slug":"stateful-rolling-piglet"}
