{"parentUuid":"e12fe40f-fbb6-45f3-bf5b-1a9840bf5d98","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"46e77d7e-3408-48fd-b50f-4c3f4002f80d","agentId":"ac7dc0987c25c56ae","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Lg9PMuv2WN9eJyhprxpKPw","type":"tool_result","content":"# IsAntichain Module Overview\n\n**Module Location:** `Mathlib.Order.Antichain`\n\n## Definition\n\n`IsAntichain` is defined as a predicate on sets where \"no two distinct elements are related.\" More formally, it states that a set satisfies a pairwise property with respect to the complement of a given relation.\n\n## Key Properties\n\nThe definition supports several important characteristics:\n\n1. **Basic Properties:**\n   - Empty sets and singleton sets are automatically antichains\n   - Subsets of antichains are antichains\n   - The property is monotone with respect to relations\n\n2. **Structural Results:**\n   - Sets that are both chains and antichains must be subsingletons\n   - The intersection of a chain and antichain is always subsingleton\n   - In partial orders, antichains cannot contain strictly comparable elements\n\n3. **Transformations:**\n   - Antichains are preserved under images and preimages with appropriate function properties\n   - The property transfers across order embeddings and isomorphisms\n   - Complementation and set difference operations preserve antichain status in boolean algebras\n\n4. **Related Concepts:**\n   - `IsStrongAntichain`: Elements cannot share a common upper bound\n   - `IsMaxAntichain`: Maximal antichains that cannot be properly extended\n   - `IsWeakAntichain`: For product orders, preventing strong comparability"}]},"uuid":"4a86be58-d3da-468b-b38a-40c6e35ea4c4","timestamp":"2026-03-15T05:23:28.679Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"e12fe40f-fbb6-45f3-bf5b-1a9840bf5d98","userType":"external","cwd":"/home/ryan/formal-conjectures","sessionId":"32eca89c-3188-4038-a46f-2447c61bd105","version":"2.1.74","gitBranch":"erdos-all","slug":"stateful-rolling-piglet"}
{"parentUuid":"4a86be58-d3da-468b-b38a-40c6e35ea4c4","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ac7dc0987c25c56ae","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_017rW4zJj3wVXhVqCZG7iycL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have all the information I need. Let me compile the findings.\n\n## Summary\n\nHere's how Mathlib's `IsAntichain` is used in `/home/ryan/formal-conjectures/FormalConjectures/ErdosProblems/497.lean`:\n\n### Imports\nThe file uses:\n- `import FormalConjectures.Util.ProblemImports` (which includes `import Mathlib`, making `IsAntichain` available)\n\n### Open Declarations\n- `open Finset Filter` (lines 35)\n- `open Classical in` (line 39 - scoped to the definition)\n\n### Theorem Statements Using IsAntichain\n\n**Definition (line 45-46):**\n```lean\nnoncomputable def dedekindNumber (n : ℕ) : ℕ :=\n  Fintype.card {F : Finset (Finset (Fin n)) // IsAntichain (· ⊆ ·) (F : Set (Finset (Fin n)))}\n```\n\nThis defines the Dedekind number as the count of antichains in the power set of an n-element set, where elements are related by the subset relation `⊆`.\n\n**Theorem (line 60-64):**\n```lean\ntheorem erdos_497 :\n    Tendsto\n      (fun n : ℕ => Real.log (dedekindNumber n : ℝ) / (Real.log 2 * (n.choose (n / 2) : ℝ)))\n      atTop (nhds 1) := by\n  sorry\n```\n\nThis uses `dedekindNumber`, which depends on `IsAntichain`.\n\n### Required Imports for IsAntichain\nAccording to Mathlib documentation, `IsAntichain` is defined in:\n- **`Mathlib.Order.Antichain`**\n\nHowever, since `ProblemImports` includes the full `import Mathlib`, this module is already transitively available. The definition describes an antichain as a set where no two distinct elements are related by a given relation (in this file's case, the subset relation)."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":596,"cache_read_input_tokens":18338,"output_tokens":510,"server_tool_use":{"web_search